dr, crazy<br>
&lt;&lt;Tanker: please write when you are sober or ?, you repeated entire paragraphs..by the way,&gt;&gt;<br>
Alas, alcohol had nothing to do with it---my wife watches me constantly.  Don't know why the damn thing duplicates.   See your generation doesn't have the patent on avoiding responsibility.<br><br>
 &lt;&lt;I refused my student deferment ...&gt;&gt;<br>
    Why?<br><br>
&lt;&lt; and went though the 6 day war there.&gt;&gt;<br>
 Well if one can pick and choose their wars, a Six Day War, would be nice--you should have waited for the Gulf War--it only lasted 100 hours.<br><br>
 &lt;&lt;So perhaps I am not the total cherry you want me to be.&gt;&gt;<br>
Wrong fellow--never was into virgins---no pun intended.<br><br>
 &lt;&lt;I stood in a trench with an UZI in my hands, sorry it was not an M 16, but the Jews make a better weapon&gt;&gt;<br>
If you are referring to the automatic version---it's too &quot;short-barreled&quot; for me.  You have to wait until they are too close.<br><br>
&lt;&lt;Tanker, stop trying to justify our past involvement.&gt;&gt;<br>
Must I? Then all we'd have to read are self-justifying comments from those who are trying to get over their guilt for having avoided sacrifice at the expense of their poorer fellow citizens.<br><br>
 &lt;&lt; and would have us all think that every soldier ran a gauntlet of spitters and baby killer screaming civilians, it just wasn't so. &gt;&gt;<br>
Never said there was a gauntlet or that it happened to everyone--but it did happen and it happened quite often.  We were warned not to wear our uniform at Berkley.  I did and no one did anything.<br><br>
&lt;&lt; Could it be, and wrongfully so, that you get sweep up into that corporate-nationalistic logic? And are seen as losers, instead of as victims????<br>
Few corporations I've encountered have displayed much &quot;logic.&quot;  As a professional, I never viewed myself as a &quot;victim.&quot;  Pissed me off, but not enough for self-pity.  Whining seems to come from those well publicized few---many of whom never served in combat--or from the &quot;protesters&quot; desperately determined to justify their lack of intestinal fortitude.<br><br>
&lt;&lt;Once more, let me say, I took no deferment, I did my 2 years, I got no G.I.Bill, I faught in a war too (in another country that did it in 6 days),&gt;&gt;<br>
They have names for people who fight in other people's wars.  Name depends on who wins.<br><br>
 &lt;&lt; I became a shrink because of being a hippy doper first,&gt;&gt;<br>
Sure it wasn't a case of &quot;doctor heal thy self?&quot;<br><br>
Hey--I've re-evaluated my opinion of you.  To a soldier, anyone who &quot;buys&quot; can't be all bad.  Malt Scotch--changed from &quot;bourbon and branch water.&quot;<br><br>
  MIKE:<br>
    Well said.  As an Advisor, I was in a group of older fellows, almost all of whom were professionals.  We viewed the whole affair from a different point of view.  We  did discuss the rights/wrongs of the war, but usully from a rather cynical point of view with gallows humor.<br>
We knew that we were the original &quot;forgotten&quot; warriors--Bob Hope and USO never visited us.  Few reporters--and they'd come to find a reason to &quot;bad-mouth&quot; ARVN.<br>
We'd comment, a bitter laugh or shrug, and get on with the &quot;job.&quot;  Didn't say it, but we all beleived in, the &quot;Duty, Honor, Country&quot; thing.<br><br>
In our small club in Hue, we had a large portrat of Uncle Ho, with the title &quot;Our Founder.&quot;<br><br>
We'd say, &quot;it's a shitty war, but it's the only one we got.&quot;<br><br>
That doesn't mean we didn't morn our dead and wounded.<br>
We started a fairly regular poker game.  I stopped going when I noticed that the &quot;regular&quot; players were changing too often.<br>
 <br>
 When people ask me what movie was most like &quot;my war&quot;--I say it was &quot;Go Tell the Spartians.&quot;  Few have ever seen it.  Doesn't have a &quot;happy&quot; ending.  Has an hororable one. <br><br>
 Old fashioned concept I am afraid.  Instead of honor, our leader's mantra is &quot;there's not one shred of evidence....&quot;  Not our idea of a role model.<br>
 
